  "research_html": "<div class=\"research-section\">\n<p class=\"research-text\">_Fragments on Poverty and Feasting_ is a modern thematic compilation of 66 passages attributed to the Athenian comic poet Aristophon, who was active in the fourth century BCE during the era of Middle Comedy. The fragments do not originate from a single play but are excerpts from various lost works, preserved because later authors quoted them for their lexical peculiarities or cultural interest. These isolated lines and short passages, which lack their original dramatic context, are unified by their focus on the twin themes of poverty and banqueting. The collected material illustrates central comic preoccupations of the period, including the hardships and social humiliations of poverty, the rituals and excesses of feasting and gluttony, and the sharp contrast between wealth and social status. The fragments often feature detailed descriptions of food and cookery, alongside appearances by stock character types such as the parasite, the miser, and the boastful cook. The fragments survive entirely through indirect transmission, having been quoted by later grammarians and compilers. The principal source is Athenaeus of Naucratis in his _Deipnosophistae_, composed around 200 CE, with additional citations found in lexicographers like Pollux. The standard modern critical edition is found in _Poetae Comici Graeci_. While Aristophon’s direct literary influence is untraceable, these fragments provide valuable evidence for the evolution of comedy from the political satire of Old Comedy toward the social and domestic concerns that would characterize New Comedy. Philologically, they offer important insights into Athenian social history, colloquial language, and the otherwise lost repertoire of Middle Comedy.</p>\n</div>",
